{{Infobox spaceflight|auto=all | name = AIM | image = AIM (transparent).png | image_caption = | mission_type = Atmospheric research | operator = [[NASA]] | website = {{url|http://aim.hamptonu.edu}} | COSPAR_ID = 2007-015A | SATCAT = 31304 | mission_duration = Elapsed: {{time interval|25 April 2007|show=ymd|sep=,}} | spacecraft_bus = [[LEOStar-2]] | manufacturer = | dry_mass = | launch_mass = {{convert|197|kg|lb}} | power = | launch_date = {{start-date|25 April 2007, 20:26:03|timezone=yes}}&nbsp;UTC | launch_rocket = [[Pegasus (rocket)|Pegasus-XL]] F38 | launch_site = ''[[Stargazer (aircraft)|Stargazer]]'', [[Vandenberg Air Force Base|Vandenberg]] Runway&nbsp;12/30 | launch_contractor = [[Orbital Sciences Corporation|Orbital Sciences]] | disposal_type = | deactivated = | last_contact = <!-- {{end-date|[insert date here]}} --> | decay_date = | orbit_epoch = 25 January 2015, 00:23:24&nbsp;UTC<ref name="n2yo">{{cite web|url=http://www.n2yo.com/satellite/?s=31304|title=AIM Satellite details 2007-015A NORAD 31304|publisher=N2YO|date=25 January 2015|accessdate=25 January 2015}}</ref> | orbit_reference = [[geocentric orbit|Geocentric]] | orbit_regime = [[Sun-synchronous orbit|Sun-synchronous]] | orbit_periapsis = {{convert|552|km|mi|sp=us}}<ref name="n2yo"/> | orbit_apoapsis = {{convert|559|km|mi|sp=us}}<ref name="n2yo"/> | orbit_inclination = 97.90&nbsp;degrees<ref name="n2yo"/> | orbit_semimajor = {{convert|6926.82|km|mi|sp=us}}<ref name="n2yo"/> | orbit_eccentricity = 0.0005254<ref name="n2yo"/> | orbit_period = 95.63&nbsp;minutes<ref name="n2yo"/> | orbit_RAAN = 159.47&nbsp;degrees<ref name="n2yo"/> | orbit_arg_periapsis = 213.55&nbsp;degrees<ref name="n2yo"/> | orbit_mean_anomaly = 15.06&nbsp;degrees<ref name="n2yo"/> | orbit_mean_motion = 15.06<ref name="n2yo"/> | orbit_rev_number = 42,300<ref name="n2yo"/> | apsis = gee }} The '''Aeronomy of Ice in the Mesosphere''' ('''AIM''') is a [[satellite]] to conduct a 26-month study of [[noctilucent cloud]]s (NLCs). It is the ninetieth [[Explorer program]] mission and is part of the [[NASA]]-funded [[Small Explorer program]] (SMEX). On April 25, 2007 AIM was boosted into a {{Convert|600|km|abbr=on}} high [[polar orbit]] by a [[Pegasus (rocket)|Pegasus-XL]] rocket, which was [[air-launch]]ed from the [[Lockheed L-1011|Lockheed L-1011 ''Stargazer'']] aircraft operated by [[Orbital Sciences]].<ref>{{cite web | author=Jeanne Ryba | title=AIM Mission - Launch | url=http://www.nasa.gov/mission_pages/aim/launch/launch-index.html | publisher=NASA | date=4 June 2007 | accessdate=2010-03-16| archiveurl= https://web.archive.org/web/20100316191155/http://www.nasa.gov/mission_pages/aim/launch/launch-index.html| archivedate= 16 March 2010 <!--DASHBot-->| deadurl= no}}</ref>
== Spacecraft and instruments == The AIM satellite is a {{Convert|200|kg|abbr=on}}, {{Convert|1.4|m|abbr=on}} by {{Convert|1.1|m|abbr=on}} spacecraft, powered by two [[solar panel|solar arrays]], carrying three instruments:<ref>{{cite web | author=Space Dynamics Laboratory | title=Programs: AIM – SOFIE | url=http://www.sdl.usu.edu/programs/aim | publisher=Utah State University Research Foundation | year=2010 | accessdate=2010-03-16}}</ref>
{| class="wikitable" |- !Illustration ! scope="col" style="width:135px;"| Instrument Name ! scope="col" style="width:50px;"| Abbr. ! Description and scientific objective |- |[[File:Cips-AIM.jpg|70px]] | <center>Cloud Imaging and Particle Size</center> | <center>'''CIPS'''</center> | The instrument has four [[camera]]s positioned at different angles, which provide multiple views of the clouds from different angles and will allow a determination of the sizes of the ice particles that make up the cloud.{{Citation needed|date=March 2011}} |- |[[File:Cde.jpg|70px]] | <center>The Cosmic Dust Experiment</center><ref name=CDE>{{cite web | author= | title=Cosmic Dust Experiment (CDE) | url=http://aim.hamptonu.edu/instrmt/cde.html | publisher=Hampton University | year=2010 | accessdate=2010-03-16}}</ref> | <center>'''CDE'''</center> | The instrument records impacts from cosmic dust particles as they enter Earth's upper atmosphere. The instrument uses fourteen [[polyvinylidene fluoride]] detectors, which emit a pulse of charge when impacted by a hypervelocity dust particle (velocity {{Convert|1|km/s|abbr=on}}). A measurement of the value and variability of the cosmic dust input will allow scientists to determine the role the particles have in PMC (Polar Mesospheric Cloud) formation. CDE is a nearly identical replica to the Student Dust Counter on the [[New Horizons]] mission.<ref name=CDE/> |- |[[File:Sophie-AIM.jpg|70px]] | <center>The Solar Occultation for Ice Experiment</center><ref name=SOFIE>{{cite web | author= | title=Solar Occultation For Ice Experiment | url=http://sofie.gats-inc.com/ | publisher=GATS, Inc | year=2010 | accessdate=2010-03-16}}</ref>
| <center>'''SOFIE'''</center> | The SOFIE experiment use solar occultation to measure cloud particles, temperature and atmospheric gases involved in forming the clouds. The instrument will reveal the mixture of chemicals that prompt NLC's formation, as well as the environment in which the clouds form.<ref name=SOFIE/> |}
== Noctilucent clouds == {{main|Noctilucent clouds}} The noctilucent clouds AIM is to study, also known as [[Polar mesospheric clouds]], occur in [[aeronomy|the Earth's atmosphere]] at high altitudes of roughly {{Convert|80|km|sp=us}} above the surface, far higher than other [[cloud]]s. The AIM mission will help determine what factors — [[temperature]], [[water vapor]], and [[dust]] particles — lead to the formation of these clouds. The clouds seem to be a relatively recent phenomenon: they were first seen in 1885, and lately seem to be occurring more frequently.<ref>{{Cite web | url=http://nasascience.nasa.gov/missions/aim | title=AIM — NASA Science | publisher=NASA | year=2010 | accessdate=2010-03-16 | archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20100324222208/http://nasascience.nasa.gov/missions/aim | archivedate=24 March 2010 | deadurl=yes | df= }}</ref> The clouds always occur during the summer season near the poles and the Northern season always starts around the same time. Scientists have found that the start of the Southern season can vary up to a month however.<ref>{{cite web|last=Fox|first=Karen|title=Clouds, Clouds, Burning Bright|url=http://www.nasa.gov/mission_pages/aim/news/notilucent-change.html|publisher=NASA}}</ref>
[[Image:Northpoleclouds AIMData c.jpg|thumb|left|Noctilucent clouds as seen by AIM]] [[File:AIM in clean room.jpg|thumb|right|AIM in clean room]] {{clear}}
