{{BLP primary sources|date=June 2013}} {{Infobox person | name = Theodore G. Paraskevakos [[Image:Theodore G. (Ted) Paraskevakos.jpg|thumb|center]] | alt = | caption = Theodore Paraskevakos in 2008 | birth_name = Theodore George Paraskevakos | birth_date = {{Birth date and age|1937|03|25}} | birth_place = [[Athens]], [[Greece]] | death_date = <!-- {{Death date and age|YYYY|MM|DD|YYYY|MM|DD}} or {{Death-date and age|Month DD, YYYY|Month DD, YYYY}} (death date then birth date) --> | death_place = | nationality = United States | other_names = | occupation = [[Inventor]], businessman | known_for = Data transmission }}
'''Theodore George “Ted” Paraskevakos''' ({{lang-el|Θεόδωρος Παρασκευάκος}}; born March 25, 1937, in [[Athens]], [[Greece]]) is a Greek-American inventor and businessman. Paraskevakos graduated from the Superior College of Electronics in Greece and served for 28 months as communications and electronics instructor in the [[Hellenic Air Force]]. He attended a variety of courses for digital engineering in [[Alabama]] and in [[Florida]].
[[Image:Caller ID receiver.jpg|thumb|The first caller identification receiver]] Paraskevakos' most notable inventions relate to the transmission of electronic data through telephone lines which formed the original basis for what is now known as [[caller ID]].<ref name="BW" /> Paraskevakos began his work in this field in 1968 while working as a communications engineer with [[SITA (IT company)|SITA]] and has since been issued over 20 [[patents]] worldwide based on this [[technology]]. His [[transmitter]]<ref>U.S. Patent #3,812,296/5-21-1974 (''Apparatus for Generating and Transmitting Digital Information'')</ref> and [[Receiver (information theory)|receiver]]<ref>U.S. Patent #3,727,003/4-10-1973 (''Decoding and Display Apparatus for Groups of Pulse Trains'')</ref> were put into practice in 1971 in a [[Boeing]] facility in [[Huntsville, Alabama]].{{citation needed|date=June 2013}}
Paraskevakos holds over 50 patents worldwide including a digital alarm communication system, which also covered handheld or portable cardiac alarms<ref>U.S. Patent #3,842,208/10-15-1974 (''Sensor Monitoring Device'')</ref> [[automatic meter reading]] and [[load management]],<ref>U.S. Patents #4,241,237/12-23-1980 and #4,455,453/1-19-1984 (''Apparatus and Method for Remote Sensor Monitoring, Metering and Control'') as well as #7,940,901/5-10-2011 (''Remote Management of Products and Services'')</ref> digital vending machine communications,<ref>U.S. Patent #4,858,743/8-22-1989 (''Vending Machine and Method for Automatic Vending and Returning of Merchandise, Particularly Videocassette Tapes'')</ref> indoor archery,<ref>U.S. Patents #4,623,145/11-18-1986 and #4,708,341/11-24-1987 (''Archery/Practice Device and Attachments Therefor'')</ref> vertical parking, intelligent currency validation network,<ref>U.S. Patents #7,006,664/2-28-2006 (''Intelligent Currency Validation Network''), #7,454,049/11-18-2008 (''System and Method for Intelligent Currency Validation''), #7,567,698/7-28-2009 (''Device and Method for Preventing Counterfeiting Using a Currency Serial Number Reader'') and #7,724,938/5-25-2010 (''System and Method for Intelligent Currency Validation'')</ref> and a method for identification of currency used in unlawful activity.<ref>Legionpatient [https://www.legionpatent.com/patents/7567698/ 698 Paraskevakos Device and method for preventing counterfeiting using a currency serial number reader]</ref> He founded, among other companies, Metretek, Inc., DataVend, Inc. and Intelligent Currency Validation Network, Inc.<ref name="BW">{{cite web|url=http://investing.businessweek.com/research/stocks/private/person.asp?personId=99411576&privcapId=84684310&previousCapId=84684310&previousTitle=ICVN,%20Inc.|title=Theodore Paraskevakos: Executive Profile & Biography|work=[[Bloomberg Businessweek]]|accessdate=20 June 2013}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.bizjournals.com/baltimore/stories/2003/11/10/smallb3.html?page=all|title=Inventor reveals the names behind numbers|last=Milani|first=Kate|date=10 November 2003|work=[[American City Business Journals]]|accessdate=20 June 2013}}</ref>
